The alpha the chef is getting comes from 4 sources:
- buybacks - this gives by far the most - Whit sells BTC to USDT and then to TAO which he transfers to the chef and then the chef stakes the tao into alpha, leaving the tao on the left side of the liquidity pool and taking the alphas from the right side of the liquidity pool, causing the price of alpha to slightly increase with every transaction

Miners will bid hashrate using knowledge commitments, saying something like
- offer id, for example `1`
- how much TH/s does the miner offer to mine (on average) per day, for example `123.567` [TH/s for a day]
- how much incentive does the miner want for it, for example `0.567` [i] (incentive is calculated in a funny way, here `0.567 i = 7224 alpha * 0.567 = 4096.008 alpha`, so a very greedy miner)
(and a miner can supply a list of these, essentially as many as they want)

now the funny thing is that they'll be using timelock encryption to do it, so that other miners won't see what your bid was until the bid cutoff time which will be like 10 blocks (2 minutes) before "midnight", upon which time all the bids are going to be revealed and both validators and miners will run a script which will tell them which offers have been accepted. Or not - we can do a version where the bids are visible from the start, but the miner who offers a given price first will be prefered over those miners that offered after him. The price would have to be rounded though. We could even do an experiment and run half of the incentive to the hidden-bids and the other half to the open bids, see which of those puts the efficiency higher. Or do it in different weeks.

The uncomfortable point is that the miners will have to provide a collateral proportional to the amount they want to bid with. If they want the collateral back, they can request it and the subnet will return it a day or two later... unless the miner fails to deliver the hashrate he offered that the subnet has accepted, upon which point a part of the collateral (superproportional) will be sent to the Chef 🧑‍🍳.
